  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Money Laundering and Financial Crimes Strategy Act\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 - Laundering of monetary instruments\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 - Engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity\n\n3. State-Level Statutes:\n- Many states have their own money laundering laws that complement federal statutes\n\n4. International Cooperation:\n- The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global standards for combating money laundering\n\nThese statutes typically:\n- Define money laundering\n- Establish reporting requirements\n- Create criminal penalties\n- Require financial institutions to implement anti-money laundering (AML) programs\n- Mandate suspicious activity reporting\n- Impose significant fines and potential imprisonment for violations\n\nThe laws are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
